adins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Oliver Merfield was born in 1370, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Charles Merfield, was 21 and his mother, Susannah Cope, was 21. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Isabel Eland. He died in 1448, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1370–1448":"1370–1448","1380–1448":"1380–1448","1390–1448":"1390–1448","1390–1485":"1390–1485","1391–Female":"1391–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1448":"1448","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1411":"1411","1485":"1485","1440":"1440","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","of Howley, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Whitley, Yorkshire, England":"Whitley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England",", England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Howley, Yorkshire, England":"